Prologue
"Please!" Queen Alwen pleaded, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, while royal advisors stood by. The queen had given birth to a girl. Just thinking about it made the Ice King frown.
The infant looked like her mother: pale blue eyes, snowy white hair dotted with strands of blue. The Ice King thought having a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, before this, he only had sons.
"You have two choices: kill this child or leave her in the wilderness. Alwen, this is your punishment." He spat out her name, as if it were poison. He always did.
The Frost Kingdom was not always a kingdom. It used to be divided into two parts, north and south. The northern part became a non-magic kingdom, while the southern part was filled with magical power. Due to the greed of the north, the two kingdoms engaged in endless warfare until the south proposed a ceasefire.
By then, the Southern Kingdom was already despairing, and its royal family was willing to do anything to prevent this bloodshed. They proposed marrying their only princess to the Northern Prince, becoming the Queen of the North, and bearing a son who would be the future king. Then, the South would merge with the North, establishing a unified kingdom. The North accepted this proposal, and Princess Alwen thus married Prince Akul.
"Please, my king, for my child's safety, you can do anything to me—lock me up, exile me, even kill me," Queen Alwen pleaded, holding her child tightly.
The Ice King looked down at his wife, his eyes filled with disgust. Maybe, just maybe, he might have a shred of pity for her. After all, this woman had accompanied him for 22 years, caring for him when he was at his lowest, and giving birth to him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace." Hearing the Ice King’s words, the queen let out a sigh of relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Alwen both showed expressions of shock. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you wish, my king," she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to an empty room in Alwen. Afterward, he commanded the guards to take Queen Alwen to the execution ground where all citizens could see.
As the guards led her to the execution ground, citizens saw their only queen—the most benevolent queen—they were about to watch her be executed, and they were furious. Some cried, others shouted trying to attack the guards, and still others wondered why such a thing was happening; but everyone shared the same question.
"Save her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Queen Alwen approached the stake, the scariest person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner for the burning. Queen Alwen would be burned alive. No one should be put to death by fire, even criminals. In the Frost Kingdom, burning was the harshest punishment.
Alwen was bound to a wooden pillar as the king began to tell how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frost Kingdom refused to believe and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the pillar on fire, and a single tear rolled down the former queen's face.
"Carly, live!" That was the end of Queen Alwen's life.
The hall was silent.
In the cold palace's south wing, a constant "ticking" sound came from the leftmost room. Passersby servants were always curious about what was inside but too afraid to get close. Maids scurried around the hall, whispering and spreading rumors. Some believed that Alwen, the late Ice King's wife, lived in that room, waiting to be freed.
They were terribly wrong. Alwen thought as she headed towards the south wing, where servants walked along the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are many rumors about it, as TA is the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you inside?" Avery whispered to this complex door, adorned with snowflakes and crowns, symbols of the royal family.
TA didn't know if she would really let him in this time, which was different from before. I still have the bruises from last time. Avery recalled this and couldn't help but laugh. Back then, Carly threw a book at him, but when she realized who it was, she apologized immediately.
A soft sound came from inside the room, seemingly saying that she couldn't go anywhere and was stuck there.
"Can I come in?" Avery asked, forgetting the consequences of his unauthorized entry last time.
There was another soft noise in the room, almost like a whisper saying "come in." Aervy felt a chill, not sure if it was from the cold or that voice. Despite having spent many years there, Aervy still found something strange about the sound coming from within the room.
"I've come in," Aervy said, slowly opening the door. To a normal person, the sight inside the room would be unusual, but it was expected. The room was filled with papers. Books lay scattered on the floor, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures. There were no windows, hardly any light. It was also colder here than anywhere else in the palace (which raised many questions). The room looked as though it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was messy and disordered.
The girl in the room was curled up on the bed, wrapped in blankets, reading a notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook are you reading?" Aervy asked, sitting beside Callie's bed.
